meta {
  name: Agent Event Notify (auth.md SET receiver, POST /agent/event/notify)
  type: http
  seq: 107
}

post {
  url: {{baseUrl}}/agent/event/notify
  body: text
  auth: none
}

headers {
  Content-Type: application/secevent+jwt
}

body:text {
  <a Security Event Token: a JWT signed by a trusted issuer, delivered as application/secevent+jwt>
}

vars:pre-request {
  baseUrl: http://localhost:8080
}

docs {
  # POST /agent/event/notify

  The auth.md `events_endpoint` — provider-driven revocation. Receives a **Security Event Token**
  (SET, [RFC 8417](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8417)) pushed by a trusted identity provider
  ([RFC 8935](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8935) push delivery) and revokes the matching
  `identity_assertion` registration at the registration layer — the provider-initiated counterpart
  to `POST /v1/agents/{registration_id}/revoke`.

  The request body is the SET, a signed compact JWT, delivered as `application/secevent+jwt`. It is
  authenticated by its signature against the **same** `[agent_auth] trusted_issuers` trust list that
  verifies ID-JAGs (§3.1) — no separate credential. The SET's `iss` selects the issuer; its `sub`
  names the ID-JAG subject to revoke; its `events` claim must contain
  `https://schemas.workos.com/events/agent/auth/identity/assertion/revoked`. The server revokes the
  `(iss, sub)` registration and records a provider-driven `revoked` audit event.

  Implicit gating: honored only when the SET's issuer is on the trust list, so a deployment with no
  trusted issuers rejects every SET with `invalid_issuer`.

  ## Response

  - `202 Accepted` (empty body) — the SET was accepted. Also returned for an unknown or
    already-revoked subject, so a replayed revocation is idempotent (no `jti` dedup store).
  - `400 Bad Request` with `{ "err", "description" }` — a malformed body (`invalid_request`), an
    untrusted/absent issuer (`invalid_issuer`), or a bad signature (`authentication_failed`).
}
